posts.excerpt: Wherever tea has been consumed and crafted over long periods, unique tea cultures with their sign
posts.name: How climate affects the taste of tea
posts.content:
Wherever tea has been consumed and crafted over long periods, unique tea cultures with their significant traditions and stories have emerged. These cultures not only produce diverse tea varieties but also present many special ways of brewing tea. The Gaiwan, an essential element of Chinese tea culture, embodies one of the most traditional methods of brewing and enjoying tea. We will show you how to master the art of tea preparation with this special vessel and immerse yourself in the traditional world of Chinese tea.

The Special Art of Tea Preparation with a Gaiwan

Gaiwan translates to "lidded bowl," which perfectly describes the look of this vessel. It is one of the oldest Chinese tea preparation methods, marked by its unparalleled simplicity. The art of tea preparation is diverse; alongside our Western teapot that we're familiar with, there are traditional methods that allow us new perspectives into the world of tea. Discover the time-honored Gaiwan, its historical roots, and its versatile uses, and expand your tea knowledge.

Glass with rolled Oolong

The Gaiwan, a traditional tea vessel with a fascinating past, originated from the chawan, a simple teacup. During the Ming Dynasty (1368 to 1644), there was a shift in tea consumption: powdered tea faded into the background while the infusion of whole-leaf teas gained popularity. It was during this period that the traditional cup received its distinctive lid, and the Gaiwan was born. The lid not only kept the water warm longer but also served as a practical strainer when pouring. Thus, the Gaiwan embodies the refined evolution of Chinese tea traditions. Varieties such as Chinese green tea, oolong, or white tea are ideal for preparing in a Gaiwan. The tea leaves have ample space to unfurl and release their full aroma while the lid prevents them from passing through when pouring.
